# Shidoka page/template generation
Default behavior in repositories where this rule is installed: treat frontend page/layout/dashboard/shell generation requests as Shidoka generation requests, even when the prompt does not explicitly say "Shidoka". Do not require explicit `kyn-*` wording from the user. Only bypass this rule when the user explicitly asks for non-Shidoka/plain-native HTML output or when the task is clearly non-UI work (backend logic, infra, package management, docs not directing UI output).
If framework, output path, route location, app entry, and global CSS location is unclear, call `get_workspace_ui_context` first. Use that tool only for syntax, file placement, routing, and integration details. Do not use workspace context as design authority.
Use `get_shidoka_support_docs` only for installation, packaging, rollout, troubleshooting, or consumer-setup questions. Do not use support docs as the primary design authority when the design context, canonical template, recipe, or snippets already answer the task. For brand-level token or WCAG contrast questions, request the `design-md` section explicitly (`sections: ['design-md']`); prefer the canonical payloads for everything structural.
For named Shidoka patterns and AI/chat/assistant surfaces, call `get_shidoka_pattern_catalog` and then `get_shidoka_pattern_context` before composing that region. AI pages must use Shidoka AI components and pattern contracts, not generic/native chat UI.
For component gaps, compose only from registered Shidoka components/atoms, Foundation grid/tokens, and approved Shidoka icons. Never invent `kyn-*` tags. If the feature cannot be built from that surface, stop and report a Shidoka component gap; build app-owned non-Shidoka UI only after explicit user approval and label it design-system debt.
For any full page or ui-shell, use the canonical `dashboardPage` archetype from the Shidoka Studio MCP. The default global switcher already includes the canonical categorical structure and visible category headings, and the bundled pattern assets already package the canonical global-switcher scaffold, workspace-switcher behavior, and widget-grid defaults, so the user does not need to ask for those explicitly.
1. **MANDATORY — All 7 generation tools for full page or ui-shell (no exceptions):** You MUST call all 7 Shidoka Studio generation tools before generating any full page or ui-shell markup. Do not skip any tool. Do not generate header, main, footer, or shell content until all 7 generation tools have been called and their output is in context. Calling only 4 tools (design context + full-page template/recipe/snippets) and skipping the 3 header-nav tools produces wrong output: missing Bridge logo, wrong workspace switcher CURRENT block, non-clickable switcher items, broken flyout formatting. Call them in this order: get_shidoka_design_context, get_canonical_full_page_template, get_canonical_full_page_recipe, get_shidoka_full_page_snippets, get_canonical_header_nav_template, get_canonical_header_nav_recipe, get_shidoka_header_nav_snippets.
1e. **If fewer than 7 tools are callable, abort with remediation:** For full page/ui-shell tasks, if any of the 7 required tools is unavailable/not callable in the current session (allowlist restrictions, stale offerings, server-name mismatch, or MCP startup issues), stop immediately and do not generate partial output. Be precise in the diagnosis: if the Shidoka Studio server appears configured/enabled in the host UI but the tool namespace is still missing, describe that as "configured but not discoverable/callable in this session" rather than "no access," and do not infer failure from empty MCP resource/template lists alone. Return a concise remediation checklist: ensure all 7 tools are allowed, toggle MCP server off/on, reload Cursor, start a new chat, then retry the same prompt.
1e.a **No policy questions on tool failure:** When the 7-tool requirement is not met, do not ask the user to choose fallback behavior (for example "strict mode vs reuse existing shell", "continue anyway", or multi-choice prompts). The only valid behavior is deterministic abort + remediation steps.
1f. **Pre-response acceptance gate (fail closed):** Before sending full page/ui-shell output, verify the generated result actually satisfies required structure. If any check fails, regenerate before responding. Required checks: (a) includes `kyn-ui-shell` with canonical `kyn-header`/`kyn-header-nav`/`kyn-header-flyouts`, `main`, and `kyn-footer`; (b) for multi-route prompts, includes shell-level `kyn-local-nav` with one `kyn-local-nav-link` per route, each link using `slot="icon"` + visible label text, and no inline button-row route navigation in page content; local-nav labels must be plain link text (not nested `kyn-link`, `a`, `button`, underline/heading wrappers, or icon-only rows); (c) for wizard/step flows, stepper items render visible text labels (no node-only circles); (d) when charts are requested, each requested chart widget contains a real `kd-chart` with non-empty `labels` and non-empty `datasets` (no empty chart containers/placeholders), and requested chart count/type pattern (for example alternating bar/line) is honored; (e) categorical flyouts (Console/Services/Administration) visibly render category heading text (red headed-category treatment), with real DOM `heading` attributes on each required `kyn-header-category` (not just circle icons + links); Services keeps the canonical tabbed flyout with masonry headed categories, and the last/only categorical cluster does not render a trailing divider; (f) overlay-in-card policy passes for dropdown/menu/popover controls inside widgets/cards (menu escapes boundaries, no clipping by neighboring cards/layout, no widget height growth while open, and behavior works for mouse + keyboard open). If these checks cannot be met, stop and report the blocker instead of emitting partial HTML.
1a. **Execute, don't menu-plan:** When a user asks to build/generate/fix a specific Shidoka page or shell, execute immediately and produce implementation output. Do not respond with option menus (for example "pick one: prompt, plan, scaffold"), planning-only choices, or confirmation gates such as "confirm and I'll implement it." Ask at most one concise clarification only when required adapter details are truly missing (framework, target file/path, route placement, or app entry). If the prompt already provides enough information, proceed without asking for confirmation. If a full page/ui-shell task has not yet loaded all 7 required generation tools, stop and load them first rather than emitting fallback/generic HTML.
1g. **No consent-gating language for complete specs:** When the user provides a requirements section/spec (including pasted content from `PROMPTS.md`, PRDs, tickets, or docs) and asks for generation, treat it as an execution request. Do not reply with "If you want, I can...", "Say build it and I'll...", or equivalent permission-seeking phrasing. Start implementation directly unless a required adapter fact is missing.
1h. **No execution play-by-play for "build it":** After an explicit execution command (for example "build it", "implement it", "generate it now"), do not narrate internal process steps such as loading tool schemas, fetching payloads, reading files, or "next I will..." progress logs. Perform the required tool calls and code edits directly. If a blocker occurs, report only the blocker and the exact missing requirement. Otherwise, return implemented files/changes, not workflow commentary.
1i. **No internal workflow UI prompts:** Do not emit internal workflow artifacts to the user (for example checklist/progress narration, "explored N files", "checked to-do list", or structured multi-choice questions for internal decisioning). Ask the user at most one concise adapter clarification only when truly required for implementation output.
1b. **No MCP payload, no generation:** If any required Shidoka generation tool call fails, returns empty content, or is unavailable, do not generate substitute/fallback UI markup. Stop and state the missing tool/payload clearly. If the server appears configured/enabled in the host UI but tools are still missing, say that it is not discoverable/callable in the current session rather than claiming there is no access. Ask for a retry only after MCP availability is restored.
1c. **Shidoka purity + shell contract (full page/ui-shell):** Full page outputs must use canonical Shidoka structure and components, not mixed generic HTML scaffolding. Required shell structure is `kyn-ui-shell` with canonical `kyn-header` + `kyn-header-nav` + `kyn-header-flyouts`, `main`, and `kyn-footer`. For multi-route outputs, include shell-level `kyn-local-nav` by default. For core controls/patterns, use Shidoka components (`kyn-button`, `kyn-text-input`, `kyn-dropdown`, `kyn-tabs`, `kyn-table*`, `kyn-widget`, etc.) rather than native `<button>`, `<input>`, `<select>`, `<table>`, or ad hoc card/list widgets unless the user explicitly asks for plain/non-Shidoka HTML.
1d. **No native form controls by default:** For Shidoka full-page/shell generation, do not emit native form controls (`<input>`, `<select>`, `<option>`, `<textarea>`, native checkbox/radio patterns, or hand-rolled tag-pickers) unless the user explicitly asks for non-Shidoka/native HTML. Use the corresponding Shidoka components from CEM context (for example `kyn-text-input`, `kyn-dropdown` + `kyn-dropdown-option`, Shidoka checkbox/radio/selectable-item patterns) so controls match design-system behavior and styling.
2. When the task is specifically about header/nav and not the rest of the page, the header-nav trio (get_canonical_header_nav_template, get_canonical_header_nav_recipe, get_shidoka_header_nav_snippets) is the minimum required set.
3. "Ui shell" means the full shell unless the user explicitly asks for a reduced shell. The user does not need to say "canonical" or list every piece.
3a. **Deterministic default:** With no request for a minimal/reduced shell, the canonical header is **identical every time** (Bridge logo in `slot="logo"`, full `kyn-header-nav` JSONSwitcher shape, all four `kyn-header-flyouts` with real triggers). Never substitute initials badges, empty right header, hamburger+search-only chrome, or a decorative side strip for this header. Product UI belongs in `main` only.
4. Treat the design-system MCP payloads as the source of truth for UI rules. When the canonical template, recipe, and snippets overlap with higher-level design context, follow the template/recipe/snippets.
4a. Canonical implementation checklist: (1) resolve only the minimum adapter facts first (framework, router shape, output path, app entry, and global CSS location), and do not read local app entry/layout or existing page/layout files before the canonical payloads except to confirm those adapter facts; (2) call the required Shidoka Studio generation tools immediately; (3) plan from the MCP payloads first and do not frame local layout review as "replace or extend it cleanly" until the canonical shell/page structure is already fixed; (4) inspect the repo only for syntax/path/integration; (5) do not use local pages/layouts/routes/component source as design authority for a new page unless the user explicitly asks to modify an existing implementation.
4a.i **Pattern-name discovery is required before rebuilding UI:** When the user names a known UI pattern or component in natural language (for example "global filter", "command palette", "workspace switcher", "local nav", or "data table"), inspect the repo for an existing local implementation matching that wording or intent before generating a new one. If a matching implementation exists, extend it in place and preserve its composition, slot contract, grouping, and interaction hierarchy. This is a narrow exception to the normal "do not use local files as design authority" rule: local code may be used to locate and reuse the existing implementation, but MCP payloads remain the design authority for new page composition.
4a.ii **Stop repo exploration once MCP context is loaded:** After you confirm the minimum adapter facts and call the required Shidoka Studio generation tools, stop deeper repo exploration. Use local repo context only for syntax, output path, routing, imports, and app-specific integration details unless the user explicitly asks to modify an existing implementation or the pattern-name discovery exception applies.
4d. **Do not preserve non-Shidoka wrappers for Shidoka generation tasks:** Existing app wrappers such as plain React/Vue layout shells, debug nav bars, or scaffold containers (for example generic `<div>`, `<nav>`, `<section>` wrappers used by starter templates) are not canonical shell authority. For full page/ui-shell tasks, replace or route around those wrappers with canonical `kyn-ui-shell` structure unless the user explicitly asks to keep the non-Shidoka wrapper.
4e. **When editing an existing local Shidoka implementation, reuse the real pattern in place:** If the user explicitly asks to fix or extend a Shidoka component/pattern already present in the repo, treat that implementation as the integration source of truth for composition and placement. Extend the actual component, slots, modal/drawer flow, tags, and actions already associated with that pattern. Preserve the original slot contract and left/right grouping instead of reshuffling product actions into a new layout. Do not create a second route-level substitute, and do not wrap hand-rolled controls inside the outer Shidoka host just to make the markup look compliant. Example failure: using `kyn-global-filter` merely as a container around a custom filter card/drawer, or stretching the search/action layout away from the real search/action/tags + filter-modal pattern.
4e.i. **Button icon edits are component-intent edits:** If the user asks for button icons/text to move left or right ("put the icons to the left of the button text", "move the icons to the right"), treat that as a `kyn-button` API edit: keep the icon in `slot="icon"` and update `iconPosition`. Preserve existing `kyn-button-group` and `kyn-side-drawer` container layout unless the user explicitly asks to move the buttons themselves. Do not satisfy icon-position requests by changing parent flex alignment, drawer footer alignment, margins, or group orientation. Use `splitLayout` only when the user explicitly wants a full-width button with text and icon separated to opposite edges.
4b. Quick thought-process rubric: good = MCP first, then minimal repo checks for syntax/path/integration; bad = using local pages/layouts/routes/component source as design authority or re-deriving workspace/global-switcher/widget-grid behavior from the consuming repo.
4c. Styling policy boundary: prefer component defaults, tokens, documented `cssProperties`, and documented `cssParts` before writing CSS. Use wrapper/helper classes for pattern layout and one app-level global stylesheet for shell glue. Do not target Shidoka component internals or direct `kyn-*` host reskins unless a documented host hook explicitly supports it.
5. Use the Shidoka Foundation grid for all main-body responsiveness. Translate the canonical `<main>` padding and direct `kd-grid` interior wrapper from the full-page template exactly — do not omit main padding, the `kd-grid` wrapper, or the required `@kyndryl-design-system/shidoka-foundation/css/grid.css` import in app-level global CSS. Unless the user explicitly asks otherwise, keep all interior `<main>` content on that `kd-grid`, using full-span columns for single-column sections. **React-specific syntax:** in JSX, translate HTML style strings to style objects (for example `style={{ padding: '...' }}`); do not emit `style="..."` in React files.
5a. **Forms / wizards:** For **multi-step** setup flows, use the **base wizard layout**: one centered wrapper (`width: min(100%, 1536px)`) containing `kyn-page-title` → **horizontal** `kyn-stepper` with **`kyn-stepper-item`** children (do **not** set `vertical` on single-column full-page wizards) → step body (fields) → Back/Next row — see **full-page-required-snippets §6a** and **page-template-builder** §3b. **Do not** build step navigation from **`kyn-badge`**, **`kyn-tag`**, or custom pill rows (that is catalog/metadata UI, not a stepper). **Do not** default to **`stepperType="status"`** for generic wizards—that Storybook mode is the status/lifecycle rail; omit `stepperType` or use the default/progress stepper for typical named steps. Use **`vertical`** on `kyn-stepper` only for **two-column** layouts (left step rail + right form), modals/narrow panels, or when the user explicitly asks for vertical/timeline steps. Otherwise use a single column flex stack with one `gap` (e.g. `1rem` or `1.5rem`) for all fields in a card; do not mix parent `gap` with heavy per-field margins. Keep Back/Next or primary actions in an action row at the **bottom of the form in `main`** (not shell `kyn-footer`), as the last flex children so buttons are not flush against the last input. **Stepper + fields + actions** share the **same** centered width; do **not** use a full-width stepper with a tiny narrow form card (“chimney”) or viewport-edge Back/Next.
5d. **Stepper text is required:** Every stepper item must include visible label text (and helper/subtext when the pattern supports it). For wizard flows, each `kyn-stepper-item` must define both `stepName`/`step-name` and `stepTitle`/`step-title`; do not rely on node-only circles. Do not use `stepperType="status"` for standard registration/deployment wizards unless the user explicitly requests status/lifecycle rails.
5b. **Catalog / listing cards:** If the prompt asks for status, deployment, and type on each card, do not emit three bare text fragments in a row (they look like broken buttons). Use Shidoka tags/badges/status patterns from CEM, optional label+value rows, and at most one clear primary action (e.g. View details)—not three equal-weight ghost text controls. Do **not** duplicate the same description twice in one card, or add a second tag row that only repeats the first as **#hashtags**. Do **not** put success/checkmark icons on every category tag (tags are taxonomy, not a checklist). When the prompt requires **search, filters, and sorting** for a catalog, include a **toolbar row** above the grid (`kyn-text-field`, dropdowns, etc.)—a bare title + cards is incomplete. **Card body:** wrap title + description + status + tags in **one** `flex-direction: column` stack with **`gap: 1rem`** (or `1.5rem`) so the status badge is not flush on the description; avoid `justify-content: space-between` on a tall fixed-height card.
5e. **Status semantics and sizing:** For status values (Active, Pending, Approved, Rejected, etc.), prefer `kyn-badge` with status-appropriate semantics over generic tags/chips. Badges, tags, and pill-style metadata treatments must stay intrinsic width (`display: inline-flex`, `width: fit-content`, `align-self: flex-start`) so they do not stretch to full-row/full-card width. Do not give them `width: 100%` or `flex: 1` unless the user explicitly asks for a full-width segmented control/treatment.
5c. **Desktop actions:** Do not default to full-width buttons (`width: 100%`) for desktop dashboards and wizards; use inline or row-based actions. Full-width stacked actions are for narrow/mobile viewports unless the user asks for mobile-first.
6. Keep `main` and `kyn-footer` as direct children of `kyn-ui-shell` — do not wrap them in an extra container. Do not add host-level `width`, `max-width`, or `margin: 0 auto` to `kyn-footer`; let `kyn-ui-shell` position the slotted footer. When pinned local nav is present, do not add extra page-scoped left padding or margin to `main` or `kyn-footer`; the shell reserves that clearance. **Footer logo must mirror header logo.**
6a. **Footer copyright is mandatory:** `kyn-footer` must always include `<span slot="copyright">Copyright © [year] Kyndryl Inc. All rights reserved.</span>` (year from runtime). Never replace this with only a prototype subtitle or “sample data” line; optional extra text may sit beside or after the legal line only if the canonical copyright remains present.
6a. Header brand lockup: keep `slot="logo"` constrained via `--kyn-header-logo-width: 120px;`, and if `appTitle` is present keep it concise and product-level (default dashboard pages: `Dashboard`). Do not use route/file labels like `Dashboard1` as `appTitle`.
6b. **Multi-page decomposition (default for multi-screen specs):** If the user asks for multiple pages, explicit routes, multiple screens/modules/flows, or provides a requirements spec with distinct sections (for example Catalog, Details, Registration, Deployment, Review), treat that as a multi-route request by default. Generate one shared shell/layout component that owns `kyn-ui-shell`, then separate routed page components that render inside that shell's `main` outlet. In React Router prefer `Routes` + `Route` + shared shell with `<Outlet />`; in Vue Router prefer a shared shell with `<router-view />`. If a prompt or support doc uses another framework's outlet wording as shorthand, translate it into the target framework's native outlet instead of emitting the foreign syntax literally. Do not collapse a clearly multi-screen requirements prompt into one giant `GeneratedPage` unless the user explicitly asks for a single-page prototype.
6c. **Local-nav default for multi-route shells:** When generating multi-page Shidoka prototypes, include `kyn-local-nav` in the shared shell by default (unless the user explicitly opts out). Emit one local-nav link per generated route/screen and include a visible icon plus label text on each link. When the prompt does not specify exact route-to-icon semantics, still assign each sibling local-nav item a different approved Shidoka icon from a neutral/canonical nav family. Do not reuse the same icon across level-one local-nav links or guess with a mixed bag of noncanonical icons. The default local-nav state stays collapsed/unpinned: do not set `pinned` unless the user explicitly asks for a pinned/open rail. Do not substitute inline button rows in main content as the primary route navigation pattern.
6d. **Navigation ownership:** For multi-page flows, shell-level navigation is the source of truth (`kyn-local-nav`). Suppress duplicate per-page cross-route nav strips (inline button/link rows for Catalog/Details/Registration/etc.) unless the user explicitly requests secondary in-page route navigation.
6e. **Local-nav link structure must be canonical:** For each `kyn-local-nav-link`, keep one icon container in `slot="icon"` (for example `<span slot="icon" class="local-nav-icon">...</span>`) and render the route label as the link's direct text content. Do not wrap labels in `kyn-link`, native `a`, `button`, heading tags, or underline wrappers, and do not emit icon-only links. Preserve the canonical icon-text rhythm from the shell local-nav pattern.
6f. **Default shell-file decomposition:** When a generation request includes substantial app chrome (`kyn-ui-shell`, `kyn-header`, header flyouts, workspace switcher, `kyn-local-nav`, `kyn-footer`, or shell-level spacing/event wiring), generate that chrome in a dedicated shared layout/shell component file by default instead of embedding all shell code inside the page component. Mount that shared shell from the framework entrypoint (`App.tsx`, `app/layout.tsx`, router layout, or equivalent), and render page-specific widgets/content inside it via children, routes, or an outlet. Prefer a wrapper layout contract (`<PlaygroundLayout><IncidentOperationsPage /></PlaygroundLayout>`) over a monolithic component that owns both shell and page content. Only collapse shell + page into one file for very small demos or when the user explicitly asks for single-file output.
7. Widget-grid arrangement and dimensions come from the canonical full-page recipe. For static dashboards default to the same page `kd-grid` using `kyn-widget` cards. Use `kyn-widget-gridstack` only when the user explicitly asks for interactive or auto-packed behavior. When gridstack is used, follow the recipe's `gridstackConfig` exactly, wrap each widget with `.grid-stack-item > .grid-stack-item-content > kyn-widget`, and do not style `.grid-stack` as a hand-rolled CSS grid/flex layout or use `.grid-stack { gap: ... }` for spacing. Widget rows must keep clearly visible horizontal and vertical separation; if adjacent rows look packed together or nearly touching, treat that as a regression and verify `gridstack-shidoka.css`, `gridstackConfig.margin: 24`, and the required `.grid-stack-item-content` wrapper before doing anything else. Do not override `.grid-stack-item-content` with `height: 100%`, custom padding, or layout rules that neutralize Gridstack's inset spacing; let the child widget fill that wrapper instead. When the widget grid is the last major content block in `main`, keep extra bottom breathing room before `kyn-footer` (for example with additional bottom padding on the surrounding grid row) so the last row does not sit tight against the footer. If the widgets include charts plus CTA/supplemental content, do not only stretch the inner card: keep the chart visibly rendered above the CTA and raise the uniform grid item height for the whole grid as needed (for example via higher `cellHeight` or a larger shared `gs-h`) so every row keeps the same vertical spacing. Default gridstack widgets must be non-draggable and non-resizable (`staticGrid: true`, `disableDrag: true`, `disableResize: true`). If the user explicitly requests interactive widgets, flip all three together: `staticGrid: false`, `disableDrag: false`, `disableResize: false`. **Cards with no chart** (text, tags, actions only): do not apply the default ~420px chart row height or chart flex-fill—use content-sized `kyn-widget` and `align-items: start` on the Foundation grid, or lower `cellHeight` if gridstack is still used.
7a. **Chart widgets cannot be hollow:** If the prompt asks for widgets that contain charts, do not emit empty chart cards/placeholders. Every requested chart widget must include a `kd-chart` instance wired with non-empty `labels` and non-empty `datasets` dummy data. Honor explicit chart-type constraints (for example alternating bar and line across six widgets).
7b. **Chart payload shape is strict:** Use `kd-chart` dataset objects with `label` + `data` arrays (not `group` + `values`). Keep `options.colorPalette` on supported Shidoka keys (default `'categorical'`), never ad-hoc values like `'chart-blue'` or custom arrays of CSS vars. In React/Svelte, ensure `labels`, `datasets`, and `options` are assigned as real element properties so charts render (not attribute-serialized placeholders).
7c. **Overlay-in-card policy (dropdowns/menus/popovers):** When an interactive overlay control is inside a container (`kyn-widget`, setup/config cards, table cards, wizard cards), its expanded surface must render above and outside that container boundary. Required behavior: menu/panel is not clipped by widget/card edges, opening does not change widget/card height, and overlay stacks above adjacent cards/layout regions for both mouse-open and keyboard-open interactions.
7d. **Authoring rule for overlays in cards:** Prefer component-level overlay/top-layer behavior (portal/body-level render when provided by the component API) over page-level CSS hacks. Do not rely on clipped parent overflow for overlay rendering. If a component renders overlays inside a clipped internal container, treat that as a component bug and use only documented host API/hooks (never ad-hoc per-page patches).
7e. **Overlay acceptance checks (must pass before output):** (1) open dropdown near the widget/card bottom edge; (2) menu extends beyond boundary and remains fully visible; (3) neighboring cards/layout do not clip it; (4) widget/card dimensions stay unchanged while open; (5) same behavior in registration/deployment wizard cards and schema/config cards. Any generated page with dropdowns in cards/widgets fails acceptance if these checks are not met.
7f. **Widget footer CTA — default sizing and placement:** When a `kyn-widget` includes a footer or secondary CTA (for example “Open costs”, “View health”), default to `kyn-button` with `kind="outline"` and `size="small"` unless the prompt requires a different emphasis. **Placement:** center the button horizontally in its row; keep the button content-sized (not full-width on desktop dashboards—see §5c). Give the action row `flex-shrink: 0` and symmetric vertical padding (for example `padding-block: 0.5rem`) so spacing above and below the CTA stays balanced relative to the body content. Do **not** pin the action row with `margin-top: auto` or force a tall strip with a fixed `min-height`—those patterns create uneven spacing. **Chart widgets:** wrap `kd-chart` + CTA in a column flex stack with a modest gap between chart block and CTA row (for example `0.75rem`). Make the chart host `flex: 1` with a `min-height` that fits the chart; use `display: flex`, `flex-direction: column`, and `justify-content: flex-end` on the chart host so extra card height accumulates **above** the chart, not as a large gap between the legend and the CTA.
8. **Overlay and flyout stacking (required when shell has drawer, modal, or header flyouts):** Prefer importing the Studio-managed shell bundle `@kyndryl-cto/shidoka-studio/styles/shell-overlays.css` in the app's global CSS file. If the workspace cannot import that bundle directly, add the equivalent fallback rules in one app-level global stylesheet such as `src/app.css`: `kyn-side-drawer, kyn-modal { position: relative; z-index: 0; }` and `kyn-header-flyout, kyn-side-drawer[open], kyn-modal[open] { position: relative; z-index: 22; }`. Do not put these rules in a page component style block.
8a. **Local nav — do not pin by default:** Do not set the `pinned` attribute on `kyn-local-nav` unless the user explicitly asks for a pinned nav rail. Omit `pinned` by default.
9. **Framework binding rules (Svelte + React):** In Svelte consuming apps, avoid repeated `$effect` loops that keep writing shell-related custom-element properties during render; set properties after mount and update from explicit handlers. Preserve canonical camelCase property names such as `headLine`, `pageTitle`, `subTitle`, `titleText`, `labelText`, `widgetTitle`, `gridstackConfig`, and `hideMenuLabel`; do not rewrite them to kebab-case. In Svelte 5, prefer event attributes for custom-element and DOM events such as `onon-flyout-toggle`, `onon-click`, `onclick`, and `onkeydown`; older `on:` directive forms are legacy/deprecated in this repo. When rich `kd-chart` props are not delivered reliably by the template syntax, hydrate `labels`, `datasets`, and `options` on the real chart element after mount/update rather than a wrapper. **React-specific hard rules:** always use camelCase custom-element props (for example `hideMenuLabel={true}`) and never emit kebab-case props like `hide-menu-label` in React JSX; always use style objects, never HTML string styles; if `heading={...}` on `kyn-header-category` does not produce a real DOM `heading` attribute, reflect it explicitly after mount; never use bare display labels as React keys for nav/workspace lists (compose keys with section/tab/category context plus index or use stable ids); avoid `change-in-update` warnings by not imperatively setting `kyn-header-nav`/`kyn-header-link` properties during every render cycle. **Vue-specific hard rule:** for `kd-chart`, do not rely only on an `immediate` watcher for the first hydration pass; always do one explicit post-mount hydration pass (`onMounted` + `nextTick` + `customElements.whenDefined('kd-chart')`) against the real chart element, then reapply on later data/size changes. For `kyn-widget-gridstack`, pass the canonical `gridstackConfig` declaratively when possible; do not bind a `layout` prop unless you have a real breakpoint-aware layout map. If HMR swaps slotted grid children, reapply a fresh `gridstackConfig` object or remount the grid. If a remount replaces `kd-chart` nodes, reapply chart `labels`, `datasets`, and `options` after the refresh.
10. Keep global switchers, local nav pinned state, drawers, modals, and dialogs closed on initial render unless the user explicitly asks for them to start open, expanded, or pinned.
